ABUJA – Prof Mahmood Yakubu, Chairman of the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) has reiterated Commitment of the commission to deploy technology to enhance the credibility of the electoral process. He has therefore avowed the commitment of the commission to improving noticeable flaws in the Bimodal Voter Accreditation System (BVAS) for optimal functionality ahead of the Governorship elections in Ekiti and Osun States. The INEC boss was addressing a meeting of Resident Electoral Commissioners (RECs) on Tuesday in Abuja. Convention: APC Governors Meet, Zone NWC Seats AMAC Chairman-Elect Appeals To Buhari To Assent Amendment… He said so far the outcome of elections conducted since the introduction of the Bimodal Voter Accreditation System (BVAS) in the Isoko South I State Constituency bye-election, followed by the Anambra State Governorship election and most recently in the FCT Area Council election has been positively adjudged by observers as credible. “However, the challenges to the optimal functionality of the device are acknowledged and we are working on them… ” So far, the BVAS has performed optimally in verifying the authenticity of PVCs and uploading images of Polling Unit results to the IReV. “We will review and improve its functionality for biometric accreditation of voters in the forthcoming bye-elections and off-season Governorship elections before the 2023 General Election. “The Commission remains convinced that the deployment of technology in our elections safeguards the integrity of the vote and provides a better guarantee for electoral credibility than the best manual process.” POLL Among issues that was addressed at meeting was the review of Election Day administration in general as he challenged the RECs to brace up for busy schedule of the commission through 2022 to 2023.